#X text 188 455 resonance;
#X text 47 60 Well see about filters in detail later on \, but we can advance that filters can go into self-oscillation and behave like oscillators., f 53;
#X text 164 419 resonance frequency;
#X text 47 109 This is a common in analog resonant filters with a high resonance setting. This happens because analog gear have an internal noise floor that can be filtered and resonate at the resonant frequency when you have a maximum resonance parameter. The [moog~] object emulates an analog filter and a resonance value of 1 is the maximum value. The object also has a very low internal noise to into self-oscillation. The waveform is a somewhat distorted sine waveform., f 53;
#X text 96 619 More about self-oscillating filters is discussed in the filters part right next., f 48;
